[normal]2.[bold]              [bold]Fairness[bold].[bold]2.1
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Ultimately f
[normal]airness 
[normal]can be considered at 
[normal]many different scales and levels 
[normal]and 
[normal]is 
[normal]a 
[normal]function of 
[normal]policy decision
[normal]s
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]Throughout the whole process of negotiations, Defra Ministers have been at pains to stress that the CAP reform must be ‘fair’ for the environment, taxpayers
[normal] and
[normal] consumers, as well as farmers
[normal]  The implementation of the r
[normal]eforms clearly must retain this broad perspective, balancing any conflicting pressures among these different actors to ensure the most effective attainment of explicit Government policy priorities. 
[normal]In the context 
[normal]of future 
[normal]CAP
[normal] 
[normal]implementation two broad type
[normal]s of issue arise: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]Modulation[bold]2.3
[normal]              
[normal]Any consideration of fairness 
[normal]in this context 
[normal]also 
[normal]needs to take into account the underlying distribution of Pillar 2 
[normal]funds between Member
[normal] States.  This continues to be based on ‘historic’ patterns of spend pre-2000, rather than any objective criteria that reflect the need for spending to achieve defined policy objective
[normal]s
[normal] through Pillar 2 support,
[normal] and results in an
[normal] extremely low UK Pillar 2 
[normal]allocation.  
[normal]Conversely
[normal],
[normal] the UK Pillar 1 allocation is close to the EU average (although there are significant differences both within the UK and between 
[normal]EU countries
[normal] and indeed, between the payment regions within England
[normal])
[normal].  
[normal]These distributional issues hav
[normal]e been subject to extensive analysis
[normal]. 
[normal] Therefore, a
[normal]ny transfer from Pillar 1 to Pillar 2 needs to be considered in this context 
[normal]- 
[normal]as
[normal] 
[normal]utilising
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]fl
[normal]exibility of EU-level regulation
[normal] to better reflect domes
[normal]tic circumstances and 
[normal]priorities
[normal].  
[normal]A
[normal] 
[normal]reduction
[normal] in the level of modulation 
[normal]resulting in reduced Pillar 2 budgets 
[normal]could effectively penalise 
[normal]those already doing the right thing by the environment and their expectations regarding ongoing access to Pillar 2 funding.
[normal]2.4
[normal]              
[normal]Regardless of the underlying positi
[normal]on t
[normal]here is n
[normal]o evidence that modulation during 
[normal]the 
[normal]current period has resulted in 
[normal]any 
[normal]comp
[normal]etitive
[normal] disadvantage
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]as a study for the European Commission has demonstrated
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]There are many 
[normal]factors, such as exchange rate
[normal] fluctuations and national taxation polic
[normal]ies
[normal], 
[normal]which
[normal] drive the relative competitiveness of farming in different countries.  
[normal]Furthermore
[normal] there is also good evidence that spending on Pillar 2 delivers both agronomic and economic benefits
[normal] in addition to enviro
[normal]nmental ones
[normal] 
[normal].
[normal]  For example 
[normal]£1m of 
[normal]HLS
[normal] expenditure generates 
[normal]2.3
[normal] 
[normal]FTE 
[normal]additional 
[normal]jobs 
[normal]and 
[normal]£1
[normal].72m additional 
[normal]spending in the local economy
[normal] (compared to no-scheme).  
[normal]Based on anticipated annual scheme spend i
[normal]n 2013 ES will sustain 778 jobs and 
[normal]generate 
[normal]£415m of spending in the local economy.
[normal]  The majority of these 
[normal]income and employment benefits are retained within the local economy (80%). 
[normal] [bold]              [bold]Environmental ambition of greening[bold]2.
[normal]5
[normal]              
[normal]The context for considering the most appropriate domestic implementation of
[normal] the greening provisions can be usefully framed in the Government response to the EFRA Committee’s previous ‘Greening
[normal] the CAP
[normal]’ inquiry. In its response, the Government agreed with the Committee’s assertion that the Commission’s ‘one size fits all’ approach
[normal] was too rigid and that it did not take into account variations in environmental circumstances or agronomic conditions
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]The response also allowed the Government to reaffirm its commitment to “ensure a better balance of benefits to costs from greening” and to continue to work to “secure greater flexibility in recognition of Member State’s agricultural and agronomic diversity
[normal]” 
[normal].
[normal]2. 
[normal]6
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]provisions for 
[normal]greening
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]agreed 
[normal]as part of the consolidated legislative text
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]provide
[normal] considerable scope for a wide-range of implementation options from the basic practices through a range of spe
[normal]cified ‘equivalent’ options or the alternative
[normal] of a 
[normal]more flexible 
[normal]certification scheme
[normal] approach
[normal].  
[normal]In this respect Defra negotiators deserve praise for securing the ability to use a more flexible national certification scheme approach as the sole route to farmers meeting their greening obligations. 
[normal]How
[normal]ever, 
[normal]it looks increasingly likely that the 
[normal]implement
[normal]ation of
[normal] greening in England 
[normal]will be 
[normal]based 
[normal]solely 
[normal]on the 
[normal]three 
[normal]basic greening practices.  
[normal]Our analysis 
[normal]suggests that
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]under this scenario,
[normal] the overwhelming majority of farms will have to do little, if anything, to comply with the b
[normal]asic greening requirements
[normal] and 
[normal]that greening in this form is unlikely to deliver measurable environmental benefits.  We 
[normal]elaborate on the other potential implicatio
[normal]ns of such an implementation decision 
[normal]in 
[normal]Section
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4 of this submission
[normal]. 
