[normal]However,
[normal] 
[normal]such an 
[normal]implementation of greening 
[normal]is unlikel
[normal]y t
[normal]o generate measurable environmen
[normal]tal benefits
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]In this context 
[normal]it will be critical that implementation decisions across the whole of the future CAP represent the 
[normal]best 
[normal]overall 
[normal]balance between minimising the public an
[normal]d private costs of delivery, minimising the risk of disallowance and maximising the 
[normal]delivery of 
[normal]environmental 
[normal]public goods
[normal] for society from public funding.
[normal] A comprehensive programme of environmental monitoring and evaluation of greening
[normal],
[normal] to enable an accur
[normal]ate assessment of the environmental benefits 
[normal]of the policy
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]will also be 
[normal]important.
[normal]4.
[normal]2
[normal]              
[normal]The relationship between sustainability and agricultural production is sometimes referred to as a balance or trade-off
[normal]: there is an assumption that actions taken to improve environmental performance decrease production and 
[normal]vice versa
[normal].  Sometimes this is the case, but often production is only increased in the short term or requires significant additional inputs.  Integrate
[normal]d actions resulting in win-win outcomes are possible, enhancing both farming’s sustainability and its productivity.  In addition, the services provided by the natural environment are vital to production.  Sustainability, by definition, is a necessary pre-r
[normal]equisite of ongoing agricultural productivity.
[normal] Evidence demonstrates that the l
[normal]onger-term sustainability of food production 
[normal]is inherently linked to the 
[normal]integration of environmental 
[normal]and agronomic 
[normal]priorities
[normal]. 
[normal]4.
[normal]3
[normal]              
[normal]E
[normal]xperience from current delivery has demons
[normal]trated that delivering 
[normal]the majority of
[normal] 
[normal]environmental 
[normal]objectives 
[normal]effectively is inherently complex 
[normal]and that Pillar 2 is 
[normal]generally 
[normal]the best tool for supporting this.  
[normal]There is no evidence that voluntary environmental land management agreements under Pillar 2 
[normal]have any significant 
[normal]negative 
[normal]impact on levels of food production or productivity
[normal] 
[normal]– the majority of evidence indicates that 
[normal]they
[normal] actually contribute to sustainable 
[normal]production eg floristic margins 
[normal]supporting
[normal] pollinators
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]5.[bold]              [bold]Lessons learnt[bold]What are the principal lessons the Government should learn from the implementation of the previous CAP[bold]?[bold]5.1
[normal]              
[normal]A r
[normal]ange of lessons learned reviews 
[normal]were 
[normal]undertaken, principally of Pillar
[normal] 1 implementation
[normal], following the 
[normal]previous
[normal] reform
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The delivery of activity under Pillar 2 of the CAP, especially Environmental Stewardship, has typically been less problematic.
[normal] 
[normal] The mid-term evaluation (MTE) of the current rural development programme
[normal] con
[normal]cluded that “
[normal]Axis 2 Measures 
[normal][
[normal]Improving the environment and countryside
[normal]]
[normal] have generally performed well, with outputs and results in line with targets and
[normal] 
[normal]broadly positive feedback from beneficiaries and stakeholders
[normal]”
[normal].
[normal]6[bold].[bold]              [bold]Conclusion[bold]6.1
[normal]              
[normal]The limited 
[normal]core 
[normal]Pillar 2 budget 
[normal]that is likely to be 
[normal]available in England 
[normal]coupled with the scale of environmental need means that it will be important that 
[normal]domestic 
[normal]implementation decisions, such as 
[normal]the transfer
[normal] 
[normal]of funds 
[normal]from Pillar 1 to Pillar 2 and the design of greenin
[normal]g in 
[normal]P
[normal]illar 1, represent the 
[normal]best 
[normal]overall 
[normal]balance between 
[normal]minimising 
[normal]the public and private costs of delivery
[normal], 
[normal]minimising the risk of disallowance
[normal] and 
[normal]maximising the 
[normal]environmental benefits for society
[normal] from public funding
[normal]. 
[normal]6.2
[normal]              
[normal]Agri-environment schemes in P
[normal]illar 2 have a proven track record of delivering environmental benefits and help to support the long-term sustainability of agricultural systems.  However, even with the maximum 
[normal]permitted 
[normal]rate of transfer from Pillar 1 to Pillar 2
[normal] 
[normal]and a future RDPE focused
[normal] on the delivery of environmental objectives it will not be possible 
[normal]for the future
[normal] programme
[normal] 
[normal]to satisfy all 
[normal]environmental policy objectives 
[normal]and there will be a need for clear and transparent
[normal] prioritisation
[normal] between objectives.
[normal]6.3
[normal]              
[normal]Natural England has 
[normal]overseen the ongoing evolution and dev
[normal]elopment of agri-environmen
[normal]t schem
[normal]es during the current programme. We have successfully delivered improvements to scheme design intended to improve environmental effectiveness alongside
[normal] 
[normal]improved customer satisfaction a
[normal]nd significant 
[normal]efficiency savings
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]6.
[normal]4
[normal]              
[normal]Natural England is working closely with D
[normal]efra, the Rural Payments Agency, Forestry Commission, Environment Agency and stakeholders 
[normal]to ensure that the transition to and implementation of the future environmental land 
[normal]management scheme under the next RDPE is a smooth as possible. 
[normal]We are also working hard to simplify 
[normal]the design of the scheme and simultaneously improve its environmental effectiveness.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]However, t
[normal]here remain considerable implementation challenges that can 
[normal]only be 
[normal]fully 
[normal]addressed when 
[normal]there is greater clarity about the 
[normal]EU
[normal] legal framework and domestic policy decisions have been confirmed.
